  <main id="ds-main">
    <header class="ds-intro" id="overview">
      <p class="ds-kicker">Intent-driven · UI concept</p>
      <h1>New-Map Authoring</h1>
      <p>
        Today the studio runs <strong>structure → meaning</strong>: it parses a map's XML, then
        <em>derives</em> what each region means. New-map authoring runs the other way —
        <strong>meaning → structure</strong>. The author states intent (teams, spawns, build space,
        wools) and the system <em>generates</em> the region / filter / apply-rule graph that
        serializes to PGM-loadable XML. This page lays out every step of that experience and the
        panels it uses, populated with real data from <code>thunder</code> — a four-team
        90°-rotational map — so a blank copy (<code>thunder_blank</code>) could, in theory, be
        authored end-to-end to a valid export. It reuses the existing design system only; no new
        primitives, no backend wiring yet.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- ════════════════════════ FLOW OVERVIEW ════════════════════════ -->
    <section class="ds-section" id="flow">
      <div class="ds-section-heading">
        <div>
          <p class="ds-kicker">The flow</p>
          <h2>Five phases, one gate — define each thing once</h2>
        </div>
        <p>Dead-simple and guided: the world seeds the steps, each step shapes one slice of intent,
           and a playability gate closes the loop before export.</p>
      </div>

      <article class="ds-example">
        <div class="ds-example-label">Authoring pipeline — world seeds it, traversability gates it</div>
        <div class="ds-panel-frame">
          <div class="workspace-scroll">
            <section class="panel-section">
              <div class="section-header section-header--ruled">
                <h2 class="section-title">Phases</h2>
                <span class="badge badge--dim">thunder_blank</span>
              </div>
              <div class="section-body">
                <div class="step-row">
                  <span class="step-dot step-dot--done"></span>
                  <span class="step-label">0 · World</span>
                  <span class="step-detail">Precomputed terrain analysis — islands, symmetry, buildability seed every later step.</span>
                </div>
                <div class="step-row">
                  <span class="step-dot"></span>
                  <span class="step-label">1 · Teams</span>
                  <span class="step-detail">Place team 0's spawn + protection once; symmetry orbit fills the other teams; protection auto-wired.</span>
                </div>
                <div class="step-row">
                  <span class="step-dot"></span>
                  <span class="step-label">2 · Build</span>
                  <span class="step-detail">The terrain is already buildable; draw only the over-void bridges. System unions them + applies the void filter.</span>
                </div>
                <div class="step-row">
                  <span class="step-dot"></span>
                  <span class="step-label">3 · Wools</span>
                  <span class="step-detail">Define one wool — colour, spawn, room, N−1 monuments; orbit fills the rest; room defense + capture auto-wired.</span>
                </div>
                <div class="step-row">
                  <span class="step-dot step-dot--running"></span>
                  <span class="step-label">Review</span>
                  <span class="step-detail">Round-trip · mirror-consistency · buildability · traversability — then export the XML.</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="section-footer section-footer--separated">
                <div class="panel-warning">
                  <strong>Build ⇄ Traversability is a loop.</strong> The closing gate is computed over the
                  build / bridge geometry, so <em>build must precede wools</em>. If a spawn can't reach a wool,
                  the gate sends you back to Build to add a bridge — it is not a separate step, it is the
                  condition for export.
                </div>
              </div>
            </section>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

